After simplifying the survival submodel to include only age and LV = 3, JM 
achieved a lower AIC and comparable overall fit. Age remained a strong
independent predictor of mortality (p < 0.0001), and severe LV dysfunction was
also significantly associated with increased hazard (p = 0.0035). In LMM, 
female sex, body surface area, and diabetes were significantly associated with
LVMI levels. Importantly, the association parameter linking the current value
of LVMI to mortality remained positive and borderline statistically significant
($\alpha$ = 1.06, p = 0.051), indicating that higher LVMI is associated with
increased mortality risk after adjusting for age and LV function. Overall, the
simplified model is more clinically interpretable and provides stable estimates
of the longitudinal-survival association.

# slope parameterization

```{r}
#reload the full dataset
heart_data <- read.csv(file.choose())

# sort long data 
heart_sorted <- heart_data %>%
  arrange(num, time)

# build subject-level survival data from earliest row per subject
jm_data <- heart_sorted %>%
  distinct(num, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% # earliest time after sorting
  mutate(status = as.integer(status)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(fuyrs),
         fuyrs > 0,
         !is.na(status))

# longitudinal data for JM: drop subject-level survival columns to avoid duplicates
heart_long <- heart_sorted %>%
  dplyr::select(-any_of(c("fuyrs", "status"))) %>% # remove if exist in long file
  distinct(num, time, .keep_all = TRUE) # remove duplicate times

# enforce measurement times within follow-up 
heart_jm <- heart_long %>%
  inner_join(jm_data %>% dplyr::select(num, fuyrs),
             by = "num") %>%
  filter(time <= fuyrs) %>% # strict to avoid stop = start
  dplyr::select(-fuyrs)

# restrict to obs that complete data for both models
lmm_vars <- c("num", "time", "log.lvmi", "hs", "sex", "age", "bsa", "lvh", 
              "dm", "lv")
ids_lmm <- heart_jm %>%
  dplyr::select(all_of(lmm_vars)) %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  distinct(num) %>%
  pull(num)

cox_vars <- c("num", "fuyrs", "status", "age", "lv")
ids_cox <- jm_data %>%
  dplyr::select(all_of(cox_vars)) %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() %>%
  distinct(num) %>%
  pull(num)

keep_ids <- intersect(ids_lmm, ids_cox)
heart_jm2 <- heart_jm %>% filter(num %in% keep_ids)
jm_data2 <- jm_data %>% filter(num %in% keep_ids)
```

```{r}
# refit models on cleaned datasets
lme3 <- lme(
  fixed = log.lvmi ~ time + hs + sex + age + bsa + lvh + dm + lv,
  random = ~ time | num,
