# jm slope parameterization

```{r}
# JM using slope parameterization
joint_fit_slope <- jointModel(
  lmeObject = lme3,
  survObject = cox4,
  timeVar = "time",
  parameterization = "slope",
  method = "piecewise-PH-aGH",
  derivForm = list(
    fixed = ~ 1, # derivative of fixed part wrt time = intercept column
    indFixed = 2, # index of time in fixef(lme_fit) 
    random = ~ 1, # derivative of random part wrt time
    indRandom = 2 # index of time in the random effects
  )
)
summary(joint_fit_slope)

AIC(joint_fit3, joint_fit_slope)
```

What was done:

Data were cleaned to satisfy JM assumptions, including removal of duplicate
time points within subjects and exclusion of measurements occurring after the
event or censoring time. Because JM requires the same subjects in both the
longitudinal and survival components, we restricted the analysis to individuals
with complete covariate information. These steps ensured consistent risk-set
construction and stable estimation of the slope parameterization.

Moreover, the slope parameterization requires alignment of the derivative of
the longitudinal trajectory with the survival risk process. To avoid
zero-length intervals and dimension mismatch between the submodels, we enforced
strictly increasing measurement times within subjects and ensured identical
subject sets across the LME and Cox components. This alignment is necessary for
valid joint likelihood construction.

Slope parameterization model interpretation:

We extended the JM by incorporating a slope parameterization to assess whether
the instantaneous rate of change in LVMI was associated with mortality risk.
Compared to the current-value model, the slope model did not improve overall
fit (AIC = 621.7 vs. 620.6 for the value model). The slope association
parameter was not statistically significant (p = 0.32), indicating that the
rate of change in LVMI was not independently associated with mortality after
adjusting for age and severe LV dysfunction. In contrast, age and severe LV
dysfunction remained strong predictors of mortality. 

# conclusion 

Extending the joint model to include the instantaneous slope of LVMI did not
improve model fit (change in AIC $\approx$ 1.2), and the slope association
parameter was not statistically significant (p = 0.32). These findings suggest
that mortality risk is more closely related to the current level of LVMI rather
than its short-term rate of change.

